FILL_CH8 = {
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>Saul's approval of Stephen's execution signals his role as an official enforcer — not a mob participant but a legal representative of the Sanhedrin's authority. The dispersion (<em>diaspora</em>) of the Jerusalem church echoes the Assyrian and Babylonian dispersions of Israel; Luke's use of the same concept transforms what appears to be catastrophe into the mechanism of the gospel's spread. Only the apostles remain — whether because they were protected by community respect (cf. 5:26) or because they understood themselves as called to Jerusalem is not explained.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Devout men (<em>eulabeis andres</em>) bury Stephen and mourn loudly — <em>kopetos megas</em> (great lamentation) is the vocabulary of formal Jewish mourning. Torah required burial of the executed (Deut 21:23); these men risk association with a condemned criminal by performing the rite. Stephen's burial and mourning contrasts with Saul's persecution: even in the moment of suppression, the community maintains its covenantal obligations.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Saul's house-to-house search (<em>kata tous oikous eisporeuomenos</em>) targeting both men and women reflects the synagogue network of Jerusalem: Christian communities met in homes, and Saul's enforcement required knowing which households were centers of the movement. The dragging (<em>surōn</em>) into prison is violent, public, and indiscriminate by gender — a detail Luke carries as evidence of the persecution's severity before the Damascus reversal.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The scattered believers preach the word everywhere (<em>diēlthon euangelizomenoi ton logon</em>): the dispersion achieves the opposite of what the persecutors intended. The Jerusalem church had been stationary for several years; the persecution provides the external pressure that activates the Acts 1:8 geographic expansion. The believers who scatter are not apostles (v.1) but ordinary disciples — the Pentecostal democratization of prophetic witness now extends to everyone in the community.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Philip goes to the city of Samaria (or 'a city of Samaria'). The Samaritans were the religiously mixed population left after the Assyrian resettlement of the northern kingdom (2 Kgs 17); they maintained their own version of the Torah and worshipped at Mount Gerizim rather than Jerusalem. Jews and Samaritans had deep mutual hostility (John 4:9 — 'Jews have no dealings with Samaritans'). Philip's Samaritan mission crosses a centuries-old ethnic-religious boundary that Jesus had already foreshadowed (Luke 10:33; John 4).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The crowds paid attention to what Philip said when they heard and saw the signs he did — the combination of authoritative proclamation and miraculous attestation is the standard Lukan pattern (2:22; 14:3). <em>Homothymadon proseirchon</em> (with one accord paying attention) echoes the unanimity of the Jerusalem community at Pentecost; the Samaritan community is drawn into the same Spirit-movement with similar communal response.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Unclean spirits crying out as they depart: the exorcism ministry in Samaria continues the pattern of Jesus's own Galilean ministry (Luke 4:33-37; 6:18). The same formula — spirits coming out 'crying with a loud voice' — appears in the synoptic exorcisms. The healings of the paralyzed and lame echo Acts 3 (Peter's temple healing). Philip's signs replicate both Jesus's own signs and Peter's earlier ones, establishing a consistent pattern of authenticated mission.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Great joy in the city (<em>chara megalē</em>): the Samaritan city's joy echoes the joy that characterized Jesus's mission (Luke 2:10; 15:7, 10; 24:52) and the Jerusalem community (Acts 2:46). Joy is Luke's signature response to salvation; its presence among Samaritans confirms that the Spirit's work is not ethnically bounded. The joy of Samaria will be reported back to Jerusalem (v.14) as evidence that the gospel has genuinely crossed the cultural barrier.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Simon the Magician (<em>mageuōn</em>) — the verb is from <em>mageia</em>, the technical term for the professional practice of spells, divination, and wonder-working common throughout the ancient Mediterranean. 'Magician' in this period was not pejorative in all circles; professional magic-practitioners (<em>magoi</em>) were well-paid consultants in Hellenistic and Roman contexts. Simon's claim to be 'someone great' (<em>legōn einai tina heauton megan</em>) is the self-promotion style of Hellenistic wonder-workers competing for patronage and reputation.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'This man is the power of God that is called Great' (<em>hē dynamis tou theou hē kaloumenē Megalē</em>): the crowd's designation of Simon reflects syncretistic language blending Jewish divine-power vocabulary with Hellenistic wonder-worker titulature. <em>Dynamis</em> (power) is a Jewish term for divine energy (cf. 'the Power' as a circumlocution for God in Matt 26:64; Mark 14:62). Calling Simon 'the Great Power of God' shows the Samaritan community applying Jewish theological vocabulary to authenticate a Hellenistic magician — the syncretism Philip's mission will displace.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Simon had amazed the Samarians for a long time with magic (<em>eksestathenai autous tais mageiais hikanon chronon</em>): <em>existēmi</em> (amaze/astonish) is used here for the effect of magic as it elsewhere describes the effect of miracles (2:7, 12; 8:9, 13). Luke's use of the same reaction-word is deliberate: the crowd cannot distinguish magic from miracle by affective response alone; what distinguishes them is the source and the content.</p>",
    "12": "<p>When they believed Philip preaching about the kingdom of God and the name of Jesus Christ, they were baptized, both men and women: the baptism formula here is 'the name of Jesus Christ' rather than the Trinitarian formula of later Christian practice. The explicit inclusion of women (<em>gynaikēs</em>) in the baptismal list is a Lukan social marker — the community that forms around the gospel includes those marginalized by both Jewish and Hellenistic social hierarchies.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Simon himself believed and was baptized (<em>episteusen kai baptistheis</em>): Luke records Simon's apparent conversion without qualification. The later episode (vv.18-24) will reveal the shallowness of that conversion; but at this point Luke presents the same language as for other conversions. Ancient commentators (Justin Martyr, Irenaeus) made Simon Magus the founder of Christian Gnosticism; Acts' portrait is more ambiguous — a man who received the sacrament but not the grace it signified.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Jerusalem apostles send Peter and John to Samaria when they hear that Samaria has received the word: the apostolic visitation functions as quality-control and communal legitimation. The Jerusalem church was the recognized center; the Samaritan conversion needed apostolic ratification to prevent schism. The sending of Peter and John — the two senior apostles, both named — signals the seriousness with which Jerusalem receives the Samaritan mission report.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Peter and John prayed for the Samaritans to receive the Holy Spirit (<em>hopōs labōsin pneuma hagion</em>): the prayer for Spirit-reception implies that water-baptism had occurred without the Spirit's manifest arrival. This sequence — baptism then Spirit — is anomalous in Acts (contrast 10:44-47 where Spirit precedes baptism; 19:5-6 where Spirit follows baptism immediately). The anomaly may reflect the Samaritans' liminal status: full incorporation required both the community's baptismal rite and the apostolic confirmation of the Spirit's acceptance.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'For he had not yet fallen on any of them; they had only been baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus' — the Spirit's non-arrival despite valid baptism is Luke's deliberate puzzle. Various theological explanations have been offered: deficiency in faith, the need for apostolic mediation, or a unique dispensational moment in the church's expansion. Luke's concern is the Spirit's role as the divine confirmation of the gospel's geographic expansion: each major crossing of a boundary (Jew → Samaritan → Gentile) receives its own Spirit-certification.</p>",
    "17": "<p>They laid their hands on them and they received the Holy Spirit: the laying on of hands (<em>epithesis tōn cheirōn</em>) is a Jewish commissioning gesture (Num 27:18-23 — Moses laying hands on Joshua) repurposed as a channel of Spirit-transmission in the early church. Its use here by apostles specifically ties the Samaritan reception to the Jerusalem apostolic community. The visible manifestation that followed (which Simon saw, v.18) presumably resembled what had happened at Pentecost.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Simon offered money (<em>prosenegken autois chrēmata</em>) for the ability to transmit the Spirit: the offer reflects his professional framework — in Hellenistic magic, extraordinary abilities could be purchased from established practitioners. The term 'simony' (selling church offices or spiritual gifts) derives from this episode. Simon misunderstands the gift as a transferable technique; his commercial approach applies the logic of the patronage economy to what is, by definition, God's sovereign gift.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Give me also this authority (<em>exousian tautēn</em>)': Simon wants the apostolic authority to confer the Spirit-gift, not just to receive it. His request reveals the category error: he is operating in a system where spiritual power hierarchies are purchasable from those higher up. Peter's response refuses the transaction entirely and reframes the economy: the gift of God (<em>dōrea tou theou</em>) cannot be obtained with silver.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Your silver perish with you' (<em>to argyrion sou syn soi eiē eis apōleian</em>): a formula of imprecation — the same doom for the man and his money together. <em>Apōleia</em> (destruction) is the NT word for eschatological judgment (Matt 7:13; Phil 1:28). Peter's severity reflects the gravity of the offense: attempting to corrupt the channel of divine grace by commercial transaction is not merely an error but a fundamental corruption of the gospel's gift-character.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'You have no share or portion in this matter' (<em>ouk estin soi meris oud klēros en tō logō toutō</em>): <em>meris</em> (share) and <em>klēros</em> (lot/inheritance) are the OT vocabulary for covenantal participation — the land portions of the twelve tribes (Josh 14-19) and the Levitical 'lot' in God himself. Peter declares that Simon is outside the covenant community despite his baptism; his 'heart is not right before God' (<em>ouk estin eutheia hē kardia sou enanti tou theou</em>).</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Repent therefore of this wickedness of yours (<em>apo tēs kakias sou tautēs</em>) and pray to the Lord that, if possible, the intent of your heart may be forgiven you' — Peter's conditional offer of forgiveness ('if possible') is remarkably hesitant. The 'intent of the heart' (<em>epinoian tēs kardias sou</em>) — the formulated plan, the considered proposal — is what requires forgiveness: Simon had calculated the commercial transaction. The condition may reflect genuine uncertainty about whether Simon's repentance would be sincere given the depth of his heart's orientation.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'You are in the gall of bitterness and in the bond of iniquity' (<em>eis cholēn pikrias kai syndesmon adikias horō se onta</em>): the gall of bitterness echoes Deut 29:18 LXX — the root of bitterness that produces apostasy. The bond of iniquity is Isa 58:6 LXX — the chains of wickedness from which Israel is to be freed. Peter diagnoses Simon's condition with the vocabulary of the covenantal curse: he is in the state that precedes Israel's exile and judgment, not the state of the gospel's liberation.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Simon's response — 'Pray for me to the Lord, that nothing of what you have said may come upon me' — is ambiguous: is it genuine repentance or merely fear of judgment? He asks the apostles to pray rather than praying himself; he focuses on avoiding punishment rather than expressing sorrow for the act. Second-century traditions developed Simon into the archheretic of early Christianity (Justin Martyr, <em>Apol.</em> 1.26; Irenaeus, <em>Adv. Haer.</em> 1.23), but Luke leaves his fate unresolved.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Peter and John returned to Jerusalem preaching to many Samaritan villages (<em>kōmas tōn Samaritōn euēngelizonto</em>): on the way back they extend the mission through the villages — the apostles who came to verify and confirm the Samaritan mission end up themselves extending it. The Jerusalem-Samaria boundary, so significant in Jewish social geography, is dissolved by the apostolic mission itself. The Samaritans are now part of the one community that Peter and John oversee.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Ethiopian eunuch was a court official (<em>dynastēs</em>) of the Candace queen of the Ethiopians, in charge of her treasury (<em>epi pasēs tēs gazēs autēs</em>). <em>Candace</em> was a title, not a personal name (Greek writers including Strabo knew of Candace of Meroe). The Ethiopian kingdom of Meroe (modern Sudan) was known to Greek and Roman writers as a distant, prestigious civilization. Eunuchs could hold high administrative positions in Hellenistic courts; they were also excluded from 'the assembly of the LORD' in Deut 23:1 — a tension Isa 56:3-5 directly addresses with a promise of inclusion.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The eunuch was reading aloud from the prophet Isaiah as he returned in his chariot. Ancient literacy was auditory — silent reading was rare and notable (Augustine describes Ambrose's silent reading as remarkable, <em>Conf.</em> 6.3). Reading aloud in a moving vehicle suggests either a high literacy level (being able to maintain focus) or a desire to hear the text. His possession of an Isaiah scroll indicates both personal religious devotion and substantial wealth — a scroll was expensive to commission.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'The Spirit said to Philip, Go over and join this chariot' (<em>proselthen kai kollēthēti tō harmatī toutō</em>): the Spirit's direct instruction links Philip's encounter to the series of divine directives in Acts (10:19-20; 13:2; 16:6-10). <em>Kollaō</em> (join/cling to) is the word for intimate association — the same word in Luke 15:15 for the prodigal son attaching himself to a citizen, and in 1 Cor 6:16-17 for sexual and spiritual union. Philip is to make immediate, close contact — not a casual inquiry but a full engagement.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'Do you understand what you are reading?' (<em>ara ge ginōskeis ha anaginōskeis</em>): the Greek wordplay — <em>ginōskeis... anaginōskeis</em> (understand... read) — may be Luke's own Greek or may reflect the actual conversation in Greek. The eunuch's response — 'how can I, unless someone guides me?' — reflects the standard assumption of Jewish hermeneutics: Scripture requires an authorized interpreter. The Qumran pesher texts (1QpHab) operate on the same assumption — the text's meaning is disclosed through a <em>moreh hatsedek</em> (Teacher of Righteousness), someone with interpretive authority.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'He invited Philip to come up and sit with him' (<em>parekAlesen ton Philippon anabanta kathisai syn autō</em>): the eunuch takes the initiative — his question (v.30) has identified Philip as a potential guide, and he acts on that identification with social decisiveness. His invitation is also a social levelling: a court treasurer inviting a travelling preacher to share his chariot is a status inversion that the episode's whole arc embodies — the insider of the Candace's court is an outsider from Israel's assembly (Deut 23:1), and the gospel dissolves the distinction.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The passage he was reading — Isa 53:7-8 — is the heart of the fourth Servant Song. 'As a sheep before its shearers is silent, so he did not open his mouth' evokes the image of passive, voiceless suffering — the Servant endures judgment without self-defence. In Jewish interpretation, the Servant figure had multiple identifications: Israel corporately, an idealized Israel, a specific prophet. The eunuch's question 'of whom does the prophet say this?' (v.34) reflects the hermeneutical openness of a thoughtful reader who knows the text is about someone specific but does not know who.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Isa 53:8 — 'In his humiliation his judgment was taken away. Who can describe his generation? For his life is taken away from the earth' — the LXX of this verse is notably different from the Hebrew MT, and it is the LXX Philip would have been reading with the eunuch. The LXX's 'his judgment was taken away in his humiliation' emphasizes the injustice of the verdict; 'who will describe his generation?' becomes a meditation on the mysterious identity of this suffering figure. The text invites interpretation.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'Tell me, about whom does the prophet say this — about himself or about someone else?' (<em>peri heautou ē peri heterou tinos</em>): this hermeneutical question mirrors the contemporary Jewish debate about whether Isa 53 referred to Isaiah himself, to Israel collectively, or to the coming Messiah. The targum on Isaiah interpreted the Servant as the Messiah but removed the suffering to Israel's enemies; the Qumran community saw a connection between the Servant and their own sufferings. Philip's answer — 'beginning from this scripture he told him the good news about Jesus' — is the interpretive tradition that identifies the suffering Servant as Jesus.</p>",
    "35": "<p>'Beginning from this scripture' (<em>arxamenos apo tēs graphēs tautēs</em>): Philip uses Isa 53 as his hermeneutical starting point, but the gospel includes more than the single passage — he 'told him the good news about Jesus' comprehensively. The pattern is the same as Jesus with the Emmaus disciples (Luke 24:27): beginning with Moses and all the prophets, explaining the things about himself. The apostolic hermeneutic reads the OT as a whole as the anticipatory story whose protagonist is Jesus.</p>",
    "36": "<p>'Look, water! What prevents me from being baptized?' (<em>idou hydōr, ti kōlyei me baptisthēnai</em>): the eunuch's question introduces the key word <em>kōlyō</em> (prevent/hinder) that recurs in Acts' barrier-crossing episodes (10:47: 'can anyone withhold (<em>kōlysai</em>) water from these people?'; 11:17: 'who was I that I could hinder (<em>kōlysai</em>) God?'). The eunuch's question anticipates and preempts the possible objection — his Deuteronomic exclusion as a eunuch (Deut 23:1) is the barrier that the gospel, in light of Isa 56:3-5, dissolves.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Verse 37 (Philip's confession requirement and the eunuch's response) is absent from the oldest and best manuscripts (P45, P74, Sinaiticus, Vaticanus) and is a later scribal addition, probably inserted to supply the baptismal formula implied but not stated. The verse is an early liturgical interpolation showing how the church formalized the baptism narrative to include an explicit faith-confession. Its absence from the critical text does not affect the narrative: baptism follows immediately on the eunuch's question.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The chariot stopped, both Philip and the eunuch went down into the water, and Philip baptized him: the immersion is physically full — both going down into (<em>katebēsan eis to hydōr... anebēsan ek tou hydōrou</em>) and up from the water. The road from Jerusalem to Gaza ran through the Judean desert; there are several small streams and ponds along this route. The spontaneous baptism with road-side water mirrors Jewish proselyte immersion (also in water, also immersive) — the eunuch's conversion uses the ritual form that already existed for Gentile entry into Israel's covenant community.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The Spirit of the Lord snatched Philip away (<em>pneuma kyriou hērpasen ton Philippon</em>): <em>harpazō</em> (snatch/seize/transport) is the verb of supernatural relocation (1 Thess 4:17 — the eschatological 'catching up'; 2 Cor 12:2-4 — Paul's heavenly vision). The eunuch 'saw him no more, and went on his way rejoicing' — his joy is the Lukan mark of salvation (cf. 8:8; Luke 15). The narrative end is the eunuch's missionary return to Ethiopia: Philip's mission is complete with a single convert who carries the gospel to Africa.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Philip found himself at Azotus (Ashdod, the Philistine city on the coastal plain) and preached through all the towns until he came to Caesarea: the coastal strip between Azotus and Caesarea was a mixed Jewish-Gentile corridor with multiple small cities (Jamnia, Joppa, Antipatris, Caesarea). Philip's extended mission through this corridor connects the Samaritan and Ethiopian missions to his long-term base in Caesarea (21:8 — 'Philip the evangelist, one of the Seven'), where he will still be active decades later.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH9 = {
  "9": {
    "2": "<p>Letters from the high priest to the Damascus synagogues: the high priest held delegated Roman authority over diaspora Jewish communities in matters of religious law. Damascus had a significant Jewish population (Josephus, <em>Jewish War</em> 2.561 — claims 10,000-18,000 Jewish residents, though this may be exaggerated). <em>Hē hodos</em> (the Way) — used here for the first time as the community's self-designation and the persecutors' identifying term — is a Jewish intertextual reference (Isa 40:3; Ps 1:6; the Qumran community also used 'the Way' for their movement).</p>",
    "3": "<p>As Saul neared Damascus, a light from heaven flashed around him (<em>periēstrapsen autōn phōs ek tou ouranou</em>): the Damascus theophany uses the vocabulary of OT divine-appearance texts — Ezekiel's chariot vision opens with lightning-light (Ezek 1:4, 13, 27-28); the Sinai appearance was fire and light (Exod 19:16-18). The midday setting — Saul traveling the 140-mile journey from Jerusalem — places the theophany in the harshest light, so that the heavenly brightness can be perceived even then. Luke's three accounts progressively intensify the theophanic elements.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me?' — the double-name vocative is the OT pattern for divine address in moments of critical commission: Abraham (Gen 22:11), Jacob (Gen 46:2), Moses (Exod 3:4), Samuel (1 Sam 3:10). The repetition conveys both intimacy and urgency. The identification of persecution of the church with persecution of Jesus reveals the solidarity between Christ and community that would become the theological center of Paul's own letters (1 Cor 12:12-27; Col 1:24).</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Who are you, Lord?' (<em>tis ei kyrie</em>): the kyrie (lord/sir) may be merely polite address, not yet the full theological title. The response — 'I am Jesus whom you are persecuting' — is the theological shock: the exalted heavenly figure who speaks to Saul with divine light and power is not God directly but the crucified Nazarene Saul has been hunting. The identification requires Saul to reprocess both the resurrection (which he had rejected) and his own mission (which he had believed was pious).</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Rise and enter the city, and you will be told what you are to do' (<em>alla anastēthi kai eiselthe eis tēn polin, kai lalēthēsetai soi ho ti se dei poiein</em>): the future passive 'you will be told' delays the commission content, building narrative tension. The same divine necessity (<em>dei</em>) that governed Jesus's journey to Jerusalem now governs Saul's entry to Damascus. The detail that Saul is dependent on being told what to do reinforces his fundamental passivity in his own conversion — he acts only in response to the divine initiative.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The men traveling with Saul heard the voice but saw no one and stood speechless (<em>eneoi</em>): the contrast between Saul's experience (light and voice) and the companions' experience (voice only, seeing nothing) is a classic feature of Jewish theophany accounts — the divine encounter is personal and asymmetric. The companions are witnesses to the event's reality but not to its content. The slight differences between the three Damascus accounts (9:7 — they heard; 22:9 — they did not hear) may reflect different aspects of the single event or use of the same word in different senses.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Saul rose from the ground and though his eyes were open he saw nothing (<em>ouden eblepen</em>): the blindness is both physical and symbolic. In OT theophany narratives, Moses could not look directly at God's glory (Exod 33:20); the blinding of Saul represents the overwhelming of his physical perception by the light that exceeded it. The leading by the hand into Damascus (<em>cheiragōgountes auton eisēgagon eis Damaskon</em>) reverses his mission — he had come to bind believers; he arrives bound to a hand, dependent and helpless.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Three days without sight, eating, or drinking: the three-day pattern in biblical narrative is the preparation period before transformation (Jonah 1:17; Hos 6:2; the resurrection on the third day). Saul's three-day fast parallels the prophet's preparation before revelation. The complete fast — neither eating nor drinking (<em>mē ephagen kai ouk epien</em>) — signals the totality of the interior upheaval: his entire orientation toward God, Israel, and the gospel has been overturned.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ananias was a disciple in Damascus: a Christian member of the Damascus community that Saul had come to arrest. His vision-dialogue with the Lord follows the call-narrative pattern of OT prophetic accounts: divine address, human response (<em>idou egō kyrie</em> — 'here I am, Lord', echoing Moses in Exod 3:4 and Isaiah in Isa 6:8), then the assignment. Ananias's subsequent hesitation (vv.13-14) mirrors Moses's objections (Exod 3:11-4:13) — the pattern of prophetic commission includes resistance before acceptance.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The street called Straight (<em>tēn rhymēn tēn kaloumenēn Eutheian</em>) is the main east-west colonnade of Damascus, still called Derb el-Mustaqim (the Straight Street) today. The archaeological persistence of the street name over two millennia is a striking example of the kind of geographical accuracy Luke demonstrates throughout Acts. The house of Judas is not further identified; the specificity of address is itself an authentication marker — the kind of detail preserved in local community memory.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Saul has seen in a vision Ananias coming to restore his sight: God prepares both the visitor and the visited simultaneously through parallel visions. The double-vision structure (10:3-6 / 10:9-16 for Peter and Cornelius) is a characteristic Lukan device for divine coordination: no single person is adequate for the encounter; God prepares both parties simultaneously. Saul's visionary anticipation of Ananias means that when Ananias arrives, Saul recognizes the fulfillment of the promise — sight restored as foretold.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Ananias's objection — 'Lord, I have heard from many about this man, how much evil he has done to your saints in Jerusalem' — uses the vocabulary of the Damascus community's received intelligence about Saul's persecution. <em>Hagiois</em> (saints/holy ones) is the self-designation of the Jerusalem community (used throughout Paul's letters for the Jerusalem collection beneficiaries). Ananias's hesitation is not lack of faith but reasonable fear — he has credible information about Saul's track record.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'He has authority from the chief priests to bind all who call on your name': the phrase 'call on your name' (<em>tous epikaloumenous to onoma sou</em>) is the Joel 2:32 promise-language (Acts 2:21) now applied to the community that has acted on Peter's Pentecost sermon. It defines the Christian community liturgically — they are those who invoke the name of Jesus in prayer and worship. Saul's mission was to arrest this community; the Damascus encounter will transform the persecutor into its most effective advocate.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'He is a chosen instrument of mine (<em>skeuos eklogēs</em>) to carry my name before the Gentiles and kings and the sons of Israel' — <em>skeuos</em> (vessel/instrument) is the pottery metaphor for human beings in divine hands (Jer 18:1-6; Rom 9:21-23; 2 Cor 4:7). <em>Eklogē</em> (election/choice) is the Pauline covenantal term for God's unconditional choosing. The threefold audience — Gentiles, kings, Israel's sons — anticipates the Acts narrative arc: Paul before Gentile crowds, Roman governors, and King Agrippa.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'For I will show him how much he must suffer for the sake of my name' (<em>hosa dei auton hyper tou onomatos mou pathein</em>): the divine necessity (<em>dei</em>) of Paul's suffering is announced at his commissioning — his apostolate is inseparable from his passion. The trajectory is established at the beginning: Paul's ministry will replicate the suffering-then-glory pattern of the Servant (Isa 53) and of Jesus himself (Luke 9:22). The promise is not conditional on obedience but structural to the commission.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Ananias laid hands on Saul and called him 'Brother Saul' (<em>Saoul adelphe</em>): the address as 'brother' is the decisive gesture of community acceptance. Ananias, who had every reason for hostility, greets the persecutor as a fellow community member — the enacted parable of the gospel's reconciliation. The laying on of hands for Spirit-reception and healing mirrors the pattern of Peter and John in Samaria (8:17); the sequence is consistent across different conversions.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Something like scales fell from his eyes (<em>epesan autou apo tōn ophthalmōn hōsei lepides</em>): <em>lepides</em> (scales) is the word for fish scales and the crusted matter that can form over diseased eyes. The restoration of physical sight is simultaneous with the restoration of spiritual orientation — the symbolic blindness of the one who had been persecuting the Lord now lifts as Ananias names him brother. He rose and was baptized immediately — no period of instruction intervenes.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Saul took food and was strengthened (<em>elaboN trophēn enethen</em>): the three-day fast broken. He spent several days with the Damascus disciples — the period is unspecified; Gal 1:17 indicates Paul went to Arabia after Damascus before returning, but Luke's narrative compresses the timeline. The transition from persecutor to community member required the Damascus Christians to adjust their understanding of Saul; his remaining with them rather than immediately returning to Jerusalem signals his new primary community allegiance.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Saul immediately proclaimed Jesus in the synagogues, saying 'He is the Son of God' (<em>hoti houtos estin ho huios tou theou</em>): 'Son of God' is the Messianic title rooted in 2 Sam 7:14, Ps 2:7, and Ps 89:26-27. In Jewish usage it was a royal-covenantal designation for the Davidic king; Saul proclaims it of Jesus in the very synagogues he had come to purge of Jesus-followers. The synagogue as the first venue for apostolic preaching (cf. 13:5, 14; 14:1; 17:1-2) reflects the Pauline pattern Luke will document throughout the journey narratives.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Is this not the man who made havoc in Jerusalem of those who called upon this name?' (<em>ho porthēsas eis Hierousalēm tous epikaloumenous to onoma touto</em>): the Damascus Jewish community's astonishment is the mirror-image of Jerusalem's later disbelief (v.26). <em>Porthēsas</em> (made havoc/ravaged) — Paul uses the same word for his own persecution career in Gal 1:13 (<em>eporthoun</em>). The community's memory of Saul is recent and vivid; his reversal is all the more striking because they remember what he was doing just days or weeks before.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Saul increased in strength and confounded the Jews in Damascus by proving that Jesus was the Christ (<em>symbibazōn hoti houtos estin ho Christos</em>): <em>symbibazō</em> (bring together, prove by comparing) is the technical term for scriptural demonstration — bringing texts together to demonstrate a conclusion. Saul's Pharisaic training made him precisely equipped for this kind of argument; his conversion gave him the conclusion that his exegetical method could now defend. The Damascus Jews are 'confounded' (<em>synecheonto</em>) — thrown into confusion by the argument they cannot counter.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The plot to kill Saul after 'many days' (<em>hikanai hēmerai</em>): the pattern of Jewish opposition culminating in assassination plots recurs throughout Acts (9:23-24; 20:3; 23:12-16; 25:3). The 'many days' accommodates the Arabian sojourn of Gal 1:17 — Paul went to Arabia (perhaps for extended reflection) and returned to Damascus before the plot forced his departure. The enemies 'were watching the gates day and night' (<em>paretēroun de kai tas pylas</em>) — a besieged-city siege-mentality applied to controlling a single dangerous individual.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Their plot was made known to Saul (<em>egnōsthē de tō Saulō hē epibolē autōn</em>): someone in the conspiracy or the city administration warned him — Luke does not explain the channel of intelligence. 2 Cor 11:32-33 adds that the governor of Damascus under King Aretas IV Philopatris was guarding the city to capture Saul, connecting the plot to broader political opposition. The combination of Jewish religious opponents and Nabataean/Roman administrative power against one man anticipates the later pattern of Paul's trials.</p>",
    "25": "<p>His disciples lowered him in a basket through an opening in the wall (<em>dia tou teichous chalasantes auton en spyridi</em>): <em>spyrida</em> is a large woven basket — the same type used in the feeding of the four thousand (Mark 8:8). Damascus was a walled city; houses in ancient cities were often built against or into the city walls, with windows overlooking the external face (cf. Josh 2:15 — Rahab's house in the Jericho wall, through which the spies escaped). The basket-lowering is the undignified comedy of the apostolic career — escaping persecution through a laundry hamper.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Saul came to Jerusalem and tried to join the disciples, but they were all afraid of him (<em>ephobounto auton pantes, mē pisteuontes hoti estin mathētēs</em>): the Jerusalem community's fear is reasonable — Saul's transformation is unknown to them, and the report may have seemed like a ruse to infiltrate the community. The three-year interval (Gal 1:18 — 'three years later I went up to Jerusalem') since the persecution would have dimmed no memories of what Saul had done to families in this community. Barnabas's role as mediator (v.27) is critical.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Barnabas brought Saul to the apostles and told them how he had seen the Lord on the road and the Lord had spoken to him (<em>kai hōs en tē hodō eiden ton kyrion kai hoti elalēsen autō</em>): Barnabas functions as the community's trust-broker. His standing — established in 4:36-37 as a man of generous integrity — provides the social capital to vouch for Saul. The double authentication (Lord appeared, Lord spoke) is the apostolic resurrection-witness credential applied to Paul's Damascus experience. Gal 1:18 identifies the visit as a fifteen-day stay to 'get acquainted with Cephas'.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Saul was with them moving freely in Jerusalem, speaking boldly in the name of the Lord (<em>en parrhēsia elalei en tō onomati tou kyriou</em>): <em>parrēsia</em> (boldness/freedom of speech) is the characteristic mark of apostolic speech throughout Acts (4:13, 29, 31; 28:31). Saul's Jerusalem presence is a public reversal — the city where he had persecuted 'the Way' is now the city where he proclaims it openly. His activity with Hellenistic Jews (v.29) matches the pattern of Stephen, whose audience he once participated in executing.</p>",
    "29": "<p>He spoke and disputed with Hellenists (<em>elalei te kai syzētei pros tous Hellēnistas</em>), and they were seeking to kill him: Saul now occupies the exact social position Stephen had — debating with Greek-speaking Jews who cannot counter the argument and so resort to violence. The Hellenists who heard Stephen (6:9 — the synagogues of Alexandria, Cyrene, Asia, Cilicia) are now hearing Saul, who was himself a Hellenistic Jew from Tarsus. His reversal is complete: the Hellenistic Jew who approved of Stephen's death is now in Stephen's position.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The brothers sent Saul to Tarsus by way of Caesarea (<em>katēgagon auton eis Kaisareian kai exapesteilan auton eis Tarson</em>): Tarsus was Saul's home city (21:39; 22:3). The Jerusalem community removes Saul from immediate danger rather than permitting martyrdom. The 'silent years' in Tarsus (probably several years, 37-43 CE approx.) are when Paul received the experiences described in 2 Cor 12:2-4 (the third heaven) and undertook the Cilician and Syrian mission implied by Gal 1:21-22. Barnabas will retrieve him from Tarsus in 11:25.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The church throughout Judea, Galilee, and Samaria had peace (<em>eirēnen eiches hē ekklēsia... oikodomimoumenē kai poreuomenē tō phobō tou kyriou</em>): the summary notice provides a historical breathing space. The three regions — Judea, Galilee, Samaria — form the geographic boundary of Jesus's ministry and of the Acts 1:8 mission mandate. The 'walking in the fear of the Lord' and 'the comfort of the Holy Spirit' formula characterizes a community growing in both moral seriousness and spiritual resource. Historical context: the respite may correspond to Caligula's reign (37-41 CE) when Roman-Jewish tensions elsewhere reduced local Jewish pressure on the church.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Peter visited the saints at Lydda (<em>dierchoumenos dia pantōn katēlthen kai pros tous hagious tous katoikountas Lydda</em>): Peter makes a pastoral tour through the coastal plain — the corridor between Jerusalem and the Mediterranean that Philip had already evangelized. Lydda (modern Lod) was a significant market town and administrative center in this region. Peter's visit is pastoral oversight — checking on established communities — rather than primary evangelism. The 'saints' who dwell there form a settled community of some duration.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Aeneas, lying on a mat for eight years, paralyzed (<em>ex etōn oktō katakenimenos epi krabattō, hos ēn paralalymenos</em>): the eight-year paralysis establishes the miracle's completeness (cf. the lame man of thirty-eight years in John 5:5; the lame man from birth in Acts 3:2). <em>Krabattos</em> (mat/pallet) is the word Jesus uses in Mark 2:9-11 — 'take up your mat and walk'. The healing of Aeneas explicitly echoes the Gospel paralytic healings, placing Peter's miracle in the chain of authenticated signs that trace back to Jesus.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'Aeneas, Jesus Christ heals you; rise and make your bed' (<em>iātai se Iēsous Christos; anastēthi kai strōson seautō</em>): the healing formula names Jesus Christ as the agent — Peter is a conduit, not a healer. The Aeneas healing is the only one in Acts where the formula is so explicit; other healings name 'the name of Jesus' but this one says 'Jesus Christ heals you' — present tense, direct agency. The command to make the bed (<em>strōson seautō</em>) confirms full physical restoration and echoes Jesus's commands to the paralyzed men to take up their mats.</p>",
    "35": "<p>All the residents of Lydda and Sharon (<em>Saron</em>) saw him and turned to the Lord: Sharon is the coastal plain stretching from Lydda north toward Caesarea — a wide, fertile corridor with multiple settlements. The mass response ('all... turned') is the Lukan summary pattern for regional evangelization (cf. 13:44: 'almost the whole city gathered'). The Lydda healing functions as a regional sign: its impact extends beyond the healing to communal conversion across a whole geographical region.</p>",
    "36": "<p>In Joppa (modern Jaffa, the port city on the coast) there was a disciple named Tabitha, or in Greek Dorcas — both names mean 'gazelle'. The dual naming (Aramaic/Hebrew and Greek) is characteristic of diaspora Jews and Jewish Christians in bilingual communities. Tabitha is described as 'full of good works and acts of charity' (<em>plērēs ergōn agathōn kai eleēmosynōn</em>) — her identity is defined by active benevolence, particularly clothing the poor widows (v.39). She represents the diaconal ministry that Acts 6 had institutionalized.</p>",
    "37": "<p>She became ill and died (<em>asthenesasan de autēn... apethanein</em>): the timing of the messengers' arrival in Lydda (two days' travel from Joppa) suggests Tabitha had just died when the community decided to send for Peter. The body was washed and laid in an upper room (<em>hyperōon</em>) — the same word as the upper room of Acts 1:13 and Luke 22:12. Jewish burial practice normally required immediate burial; the decision to wash but not yet bury implies the community hoped Peter could reverse the death.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The disciples in Joppa heard that Peter was in Lydda and sent two men to him (<em>apesteilan duo andras pros auton parakalountes, Mē oknēsēs dielthein heōs hēmōn</em>): 'Do not delay coming to us'. The urgency of the appeal — 'do not hesitate/delay' — implies the community knew what Peter had done in Lydda and believed he could act similarly for Tabitha. The two-messenger pattern mirrors the Jewish legal minimum for testimony (Deut 19:15); the messengers are both witnesses to the death and authenticators of the resurrection.</p>",
    "39": "<p>All the widows stood beside Peter weeping, showing him tunics and garments Dorcas had made while she was with them (<em>epideiknymenai chitōnas kai himatia hosa epoiei met autōn Dorkos</em>): the widows display the garments as evidence of Tabitha's ministry and as a plea for her restoration. In the ancient world, widows were among the most economically vulnerable — typically dependent on their deceased husbands' households or on community support. Tabitha's clothing-ministry was a direct material lifeline, and the widows' grief is not merely personal but practical.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Peter put all the widows and weepers outside, knelt and prayed, then turned to the body and said 'Tabitha, rise' (<em>Tabeitha anastēthi</em>): the expulsion of mourners and the private prayer before the miracle directly echoes Elijah (1 Kgs 17:19-20) and Elisha (2 Kgs 4:33-35) — both of whom withdrew with the dead child alone before the miracle. The Aramaic address 'Tabitha' (not 'Dorcas') confirms local tradition; it is the same pattern as Jesus's 'Talitha koum' to Jairus's daughter (Mark 5:41), which Aramaic readers would recognize as virtually identical in sound.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Peter gave her his hand and raised her up (<em>dous de autē cheira anestēsen autēn</em>): the hand-raising gesture is the same as Peter's lifting of the lame man in Acts 3:7. The physical gesture of raising connects healing and resurrection — the hand-up is both literal rehabilitation and the enacted sign of resurrection-life. 'He called the saints and widows, presenting her alive' (<em>parestēsen autēn zōsan</em>): the word <em>paristēmi</em> (present) with <em>zōsan</em> (alive) is the language of legal presentation of evidence — Peter presents Tabitha as proof of her resurrection.</p>",
    "42": "<p>It became known throughout all Joppa, and many believed in the Lord (<em>egnōsthē de holēn tēn Ioppēn kai episteusan polloi epi ton kyrion</em>): the pattern of miracle → community proclamation → mass conversion is consistent with the Lydda/Sharon response (v.35). Joppa was a port city — exposure to the event and its report would be rapid and wide. The parallelism between the Lydda and Joppa miracles (paralytic healed, dead raised; both cities respond) is Luke's literary shaping of the Petrine ministry as a coherent attestation sequence.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Peter stayed in Joppa for many days with one Simon, a tanner (<em>para tini Simōni burssei</em>): a tanner worked with animal hides, a process requiring dead animals and various chemical processes that made the trade ceremonially unclean in Jewish law — the Mishnah (m. Ketubot 7:10) lists tanners among professions whose wives could claim divorce due to the smell. Peter's choice to stay with a tanner signals the beginning of his movement toward Gentile inclusion (the next episode is Cornelius). His location in a trade house on the social periphery is deliberate preparation for what follows in chapter 10.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'acts')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH8)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH9)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'acts', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Acts mkt-context: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
